  1. The color= year code makes it continuous variable while color = as.character (year) makes it categorical. There is no right or wrong here or which one is better. I think this depends on the use. We can make a data into categorical as well continuous depending on the need.
library(tidyverse)
# Graph 1
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x=hwy, y=cty, color=year))

# Graph 2
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color = as.character(year)))

  1. Below is mapping of a continuous variable to size, and shape. A continuous varable cannot be mapped to shape. The shape palette can only deal with 6 discrete values because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate. A continuous variable with color aesthetics is seen as a band of colors from light whereas categotical values are seen as one color for each category.
library(tidyverse)
# Mapping continuous variable to size
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x=hwy, y=cty, size=cyl))

#Mapping continuous variable to shape (categorical)
#ggplot(data = mpg) +
#geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, shape = cyl))

# Mapping categorical variable to size
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x=hwy, y=cty, size=trans))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

# Mapping categorical variable to shape
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, shape = trans))

2.3 Grammar of graphics: Facets

  1. Facets looks at the variable and instruction. It looks at our instruction if needs to draw columns or rows. It then looks at the variable according to which it divides the grids. If variable is categorical and has 3 categories, it will create three grids. One can creates columns as well as rows as in the graph #3 below.
library(tidyverse)
#graph 1
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
facet_grid(cols = vars(drv))

#graph 2
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
facet_grid(rows = vars(year))

#graph 3
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
facet_grid(rows = vars(year), cols = vars(drv))

  1. As I tried below, facet_grd tried to create too many columns for each value of continuous variable. This doesnt make sense and is hardly visible.
library(tidyverse)
# trying graph with continuous variable
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
facet_grid(cols = vars(displ))

  1. Facet_wrap is creating seperate grids instead of using color aesthetics where it is using different colors in one grid. Facet_wrap is useful if there are limited grids such as categorical or continuous but with limited values.

In this case or the code given facet_wrap works fine as there are only two years. But otherwise if you want to see all of the values differentiation at once it will be harder to compare all facets. It would be harder to find a connection in between whereas color aesthetics would work fine if small data. Finding outliers and looking at the concentration would be easier in color aesthetics.

If it is a large data set differentiating with facet_wrap would be a better way as in case of color aesthetics the points will overlap each other or will be too close to differentiate.

library(tidyverse)
#using facet_wrap instead of color aesthetics
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
facet_wrap(vars(year), nrow = 2)

# using color aesthetic insteaed of facet_wrap
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = year))

  1. nrow and ncol in facet_wrap controlls how many columnns and rows of facets grids will have. Other options to control layout are scales that control: scales - if scales to be fixed or free or free with one dimension like x or y axis dir - controls direction horizontal or vertical. as.table - If TRUE, the default, the facets are laid out like a table with highest values at the bottom-right. If FALSE, the facets are laid out like a plot with the highest value at the top-right. (r studio function help) strip.position - By default, the labels are displayed on the top of the plot. Using strip.position it is possible to place the labels on either of the four sides by setting strip.position = c(top,bottom,left,right) (r help)

nrow and ncol are not there in facet_grid because they are controlled by the variables.

  1. Rotating x axis labels. (used the R genomics documentation Prof Marian Schmidt of University of Michigan) (https://rpubs.com/marschmi/118588)
library(tidyverse)
#rotating the x axis labels by 45 degrees using code from the documentation referenced above.
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy, color=class)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=0)) +
facet_grid(vars(year))

  1. Reproducing the graph. The shape palette can only deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because we have more than 6 manufacturers, it becomes difficult to discriminate.
library(tidyverse)
#Reproducing the graph
ggplot(data = mpg) +
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = manufacturer)) +

  1. Continuing to use the shape aesthetic and fixing the graph such that there is a shape for every manufacturer.

(I used R studio cheat sheet to get the shapes) (https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ggplot2-cheatsheet.pdf)

library(tidyverse)
#Reproducing the graph
ggplot(data = mpg) +
scale_shape_manual(values = c(0:25)) + 
geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = manufacturer)) +
facet_grid(year~drv)
